    "narrative": "The Austin Waves enter today\u2019s slate with a clear focus on exploiting platoon advantages and targeting favorable matchups against soft-tossing starting rotations. **Luis Robert Jr.** (75.28) and **Kyle Tucker** (74.59) stand as the premier anchors of the lineup, boasting the highest daily efficiency scores due to their elite power-speed profiles. **Luis Robert Jr.** benefits significantly from a dynamic platoon edge against the vulnerable Quintana, while **Kyle Tucker** remains a must-start despite facing the challenging Imanaga, as the projected wind-out conditions provide enough lift to negate the lefty-on-lefty matchup risk. **Jackson Merrill** (67.91) and **Josh Lowe** (66.91) also earn strong consideration; **Josh Lowe** specifically benefits from an impressive 14% boost via the platoon advantage, making him a high-upside play despite the presence of a tough arm in Lugo.\n\nOur toughest roster management decision involved leaving **Gunnar Henderson** (53.01) on the bench. While his talent is undeniable, the extreme SP skill of Early makes the matchup a statistical trap, causing **Gunnar Henderson** to fall below the efficiency floors established by the rest of our starting nine. Similarly, **Marcell Ozuna** (51.73) fell just shy of the threshold due to a lack of elite speed-category contribution, which remains our primary tie-breaker given the high weight placed on SB in this format. We are keeping a close eye on the \"Lineup Pending\" status for **Kyle Tucker**, **Josh Lowe**, **Andy Pages**, and **Nolan Schanuel**; should these players slide down the batting order once official lineups are posted, their scores\u2014and our reliance on them for run production\u2014may be subject to revision. \n\nThe middle-infield rotation of **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.**, **Nasim Nunez**, and **Jacob Wilson** serves as our primary engine for stolen base production today. **Nasim Nunez** (60.54) sees a nice surge against the weaker arm of Hudson, providing a safety net for our SB category even as we sacrifice some upside in the counting stats. We remain cautious with **Liam Hicks** (56.03) and **Drake Baldwin** (55.63), both of whom are hovering near the marginal tier. While they represent our best options at the Catcher slots today, their utility is strictly dependent on capitalizing on mid-rotation order spots. With **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (66.71) anchoring first base, we expect the heavy lifting in RBI to come from the heart of the order, provided the conditions hold through the early innings.",
